04462nam a22005415i 9780822383024DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19931993ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223830247 a10.1515/97808223830242doi  a(DE-B1597)552082  a(OCoLC)841913351  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPQ7797.B635bZ623 1993 7aLIT0041002bisacsh04a8682201 aBalderston, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOut of Context :bHistorical Reference and the Representation of Reality in Borges /cDaniel Balderston. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction: History, Politics, and Literature in Borges -- t2 Menard and His Contemporaries: The Arms and Letters Debate -- t3 The "Labyrinth of Trenches without Any Plan" in "El jardin de senderos que se bifurcan" -- t4- Prague, March 1939: Recovering the Historicity of "El milagro secreto" -- t5 Cryptogram and Scripture: Losing Count in "La escritura del dios" -- t6 Going Native: Beyond Civilization and Savagery in "Historia del guerrero y de la cautiva" -- t7 On the Threshold of Otherness: British India in "£1 hombre en el umbra!" -- t8 Behind Closed Doors: The Guayaquil Meeting and the Silences of History -- t9 Conclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Jorge Luis Borges's finely wrought, fantastic stories, so filigreed with strange allusions, critics have consistently found little to relate to the external world, to history--in short, to reality. Out of Context corrects this shortsighted view and reveals the very real basis of the Argentine master's purported "irreality." By providing the historical context for some of the writer's best-loved and least understood works, this study also gives us a new sense of Borges's place within the context of contemporary literature.Through a detailed examination of seven stories, Daniel Balderston shows how Borges's historical and political references, so often misread as part of a literary game, actually open up a much more complex reality than the one made explicit to the reader. Working in tension with the fantastic aspects of Borges' work, these precise references to realities outside the text illuminate relations between literature and history as well as the author's particular understanding of both. In Borges's perspective as it is revealed here, history emerges as an "other" only partially recoverable in narrative form. From what can be recovered, Balderston is able to clarify Borges's position on historical episodes and trends such as colonialism, the Peronist movement, "Western culture," militarism, and the Spanish invasion of the Americas.Informed by a wide reading of history, a sympathetic use of critical theory, and a deep understanding of Borges's work, this iconoclastic study provides a radical new approach to one of the most celebrated and-until now-hermetic authors of our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aHistory in literature. 0aReality in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383024zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822383024.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles